Incident.Summary: A vehicle was stopped for driving on a highway faster than the posted speed limit (55mph). Upon contact with the vehicle, the strong odor of Cannabis was detected and the subsequent probable-cause search revealed civil Marijuana.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText: This incident was recorded on an in-car and body-worn camera system (H-27). Scene Processing: Upon contact with the driver, the sole occupant, I detected the strong odor of Marijuana emitting from the vehicle. The subsequent search of the vehicle yielded one clear plastic baggie containing suspected Marijuana (Weight was 0.5 grams) and one tray containing residue, both recovered from the front passenger seat of the vehicle. The CDS was processed according to MSP policies and procedures, and stored in the Barrack H Property Room. The CDS was recorded on a MSP Form 67, Chain of Custody, and Property Recorded P-342538, and held at the Maryland State Police La Plata Barrack. Physical Evidence: The following item was recovered from the vehicle during a probable cause search and recorded on Property Held P-342538: One clear Ziploc bag labeled A, containing one clear plastic baggie and suspected Marijuana. One clear Ziploc bag labeled B, containing one black and red metal tray with suspected Marijuana residue. Driver: Palmore, Jamiyal Rene (DOB: 11/03/1994). Traffic Violation: TA 21-801.1 Exceeding posted maximum speed limit (0390YK1) TA 13-411(f) Displaying expired registration plate issued by any state. Civil Offense: CR 5-601(C)(2)ii(2) CDS-Possess-Cannabis less than 1.5 ounces. Tracking #4Z46644476 NARRATIVE: On Sunday, January 16, 2023, at approximately 0959 hours, I was sitting stationary in my marked MSP patrol vehicle (H-27), in the crossover of MD Route 301 north of Balsum Run, Bel Alton, Charles County, MD 20611. I was facing West observing southbound traffic, when I observed a Silver Dodge Journey at what appeared to be traveling at a high rate of speed, southbound in lane one. Utilizing Pro Laser III (PL14773) I was able to detect the vehicle was traveling 80 MPH in a 55MPH zone. I activated my emergency equipment and initiated a traffic stop on the vehicle bearing Maryland temporary tag T1086979. The Dodge Journey pulled over on the right shoulder at Chapel Point Road. The Maryland State Police La Plata Barrack Police Communications Officer advised the registration was expired (1/1/2023). Prior to making contact with the driver as the window of the vehicle rolled down large white cloud of smoke escaped from the vehicle. I made contact with the driver, the sole occupant, of the vehicle and stated the reason for the traffic stop. I instructed the driver to retrieve his license and registration. The driver complied, and I was able to identify him by his DC drivers license as Palmore, Jamiyal Rene (AA/M DOB: 11/03/1994). While speaking with Palmore, I detected the strong odor of Marijuana emitting from his vehicle. I explained to Palmore, I detected the strong odor of Marijuana emitting from his vehicle and that I would be searching it. I asked Palmore if he had any Marijuana in the vehicle he stated No. A probable cause search of the Dodge Journey revealed one clear plastic baggie inside a black and red metal tray containing suspected Marijuana and residue. Both recovered from the front passenger side of the Dodge. I recognized the CDS to be Marijuana, a controlled dangerous substance, from my knowledge, training, and experience I gained while at the Maryland State Police Academy, and previous CDS violations. Palmore was issued a Uniform Civil Citation (6Z46643477) on scene as well as traffic citations for exceeding the posted speed limit and a warning for expired registration. All CDS was packaged according to Maryland state police policies and stored in the La Plata storage locker. All events occurred in Charles County, MD. Case Closed.
